                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>Thin slab of white marble, broken vertically in two and subsequently reconnected. The edges are all lightly damaged (chipped), with a couple of the letters along the top edge partially obscured, and the bottom edge is more heavily damaged; the stone is otherwise intact. The rear is finished and smooth.</p>
                                    <material ana="#material.stone.marble" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/48.html">marble (white)</material>
                                    <objectType ana="#object.plaque" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/259.html">plaque</objectType>
                                    <dimensions>
                                        <height unit="cm">29.5</height>
                                        <width unit="cm">46</width>
                                        <depth unit="cm">1.6-2</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition ana="#condition.complete"/>
		    </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><p>A single line of Hebrew is followed by 14 lines of Latin; the Latin text observes a more or less regular left margin, irregular on the right. The lower right and left corners contain small incised menorahs, with the last line of text between them consisting simply of 'overspill' from the preceding line, offset towards the right.</p>
                                    <rs ana="#execution.chiselled" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1">chiselled</rs>
                                	<damage ana="#text-condition.legible"/>
			</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>
                                <p>Letters generally neatly and regularly cut, with basic serifs on the long strokes. B is somewhat irregular in fomration, sometimes with equal loops, sometimes with smaller upper loop; C is large and open; E is narrow, with three short equal horizontal strokes; G has distinctive form of small C with a tail descending to lower right; M is formed of four equal diagonal strokes; P has a somewhat elongated frequently (but not always) closed loop, but some instances have a wide horizaontal foot also; Q is closed with a trailing tail;  R is usually closed, with a tail usually straight and extended but finishing above the line; S is frequently oversize. The two menorahs at the foot of the inscription are 15 mm and 23 mm (the left is incomplete).</p>
                                <locus from="line1" to="line1">Line 1</locus>
